Abstract = {Existing guidelines for salinity and sodicity, as well as related management recommendations, were developed for generalized use, without consideration of the specific soil, chemical, physical, climatic and plant conditions at each location. Recent advances in instrumentation, increased understanding of the physical and chemical processes, and development of sophisticated computer simulation programs now allow us to develop more site specific management recommendations. New instrumentation technology exists for rapid remote sensing of salinity and representation of the spatial distribution. This information can be utilized to diagnose the cause of the salinity problem and devise a water efficient reclamation strategy. Simulation models can be used as tools to evaluate the extent to which the soil chemical or physical properties need to be modified, taking into consideration the available drainage, evapotranspiration requirements, water quality and quantity, crop salt tolerance and acceptable relative yield. Applications to management problems include evaluation of when to use supplemental saline water for irrigation during late crop stage if fresh water is not available and as well as evaluation of plant response to ion balances and osmotic pressure. Other examples include sodic soil management options where, rather than specify a fixed exchangeable sodium percentage, the user can allow for tradeoff of water quantity, amendment type and mode of application, green manuring etc., taking into consideration the different time requirements for different soil types and different reclamation practices.},
