Abstract = {A simple model which predicts radiance reflectance below the waters surface as a function of the concentrations of chlorophyll, colored dissolved organic matter (CDOM), and suspended particulate inorganic material (SPIM) is described. Model optimisations which matched simulated radiance reflectance to measured reflectance spectra by adjusting the model concentrations of chlorophyll, CDOM and SPIM yielded simulated reflectance spectra which closely matched the measured data. The concentrations of chlorophyll, CDOM and SPIM obtained by the optimisation procedure were in reasonable agreement which measured data. To estimate the variability of radiance reflectance in Lake Malaren (central Sweden); nurmeric distributions of chlorophyll, CDOM and SPIM concentrations were derived from a long term water quality monitoring data base. The distributions of these parameters defined realistic ranges for use in univariate and multivariate sensitivity analysis of radiance reflectance. Variations in radiance reflectance were most strongly influenced by variations in SPIM, and CDOM. CDOM related variations in radiance reflectance significantly overlap with variations in radiance reflectance resulting from changes in chlorophyll concentration. As a result estimation of chlorophyll from radiance reflectance was limited to concentrations above a threshold value of approximately 8 mug l(-1). Multivariate sensitivity analysis defined ranges of variation in radiance reflectance which are well matched to the spatial variability in field measurements.},
